False negative corrections

We here look at how long the individual cows have been infected with each pathogen group, detected using BC. Prior to analysis, we corrected the (assumed) false negative records to positive (if one negative result was found between two positive results). In herd 1 there were 32 corrections for Major pathogens, 80 corrections for Minor pathogens and 12 for Other pathogens. In herd 2 there were 18 corrections for Major pathogens, 62 for Minor pathogens and 17 for Other pathogens.

Inclusion criteria

Should we use the records with SCC < 50K?

We use all of it where SCC is not missing and above 0. We then set missing DSCC values to half of the lowest value (within the same herd). A practical solution that kind of reflect the DSCC level in the herd.

The minimum DSCC for Herd 1 is 34.05 and for Herd 2 it is 25.09.

New / Chronic infections

Then we identify the chronic cows and the new infections. New infections are positive records where there was a negative record in the previous sampling. Chronic infections are positive records where the previous record was positive.

Does this make sense to do on cow level, or should we go down to quarter level?

# Function to identify new infections:
# Først negativ og så positive = new infection
f.new <- function(x)
  {
    y <- rep(0,length(x))
    y[c(NA,diff(x))%in%1 & x==1] <- 1
    return(y)
  }

# Function to identify chronic infections:
# Smittet to gange i træk = chronic
f.chronic <- function(x)
  {
    y <- rep(0,length(x))
    y[c(NA,diff(x))%in%0 & x==1] <- 1
    return(y)
  }

#Et eksempel til at bygge med:
#i <- 2665
#i <- 3047

# We loop over the cows and find the new infections and the chronic cases:
kowz <- unique(alldata$Cow.ID[alldata$major2==1])
for(i in kowz)
{
  tmp.maj <- alldata[Cow.ID==i]$major
  tmp.min <- alldata[Cow.ID==i]$minor
  tmp.oth <- alldata[Cow.ID==i]$other

  alldata[Cow.ID==i]$newinf.maj <- f.new(tmp.maj)
  alldata[Cow.ID==i]$newinf.min <- f.new(tmp.min)
  alldata[Cow.ID==i]$newinf.oth <- f.new(tmp.oth)

  alldata[Cow.ID==i]$chronic.maj <- f.chronic(tmp.maj)
  alldata[Cow.ID==i]$chronic.min <- f.chronic(tmp.min)
  alldata[Cow.ID==i]$chronic.oth <- f.chronic(tmp.oth)

}

Sensitivity and specificity SCC

We calculate the sensitivity and specificity for using a fixed threshold for SCC and DSCC separately. and in combination.

Herd 1:

cutoff.scc <- 200
cutoffs <- seq(50,400,50)

dt <- alldata[Herd==1]

res.tmp <- as.data.frame(matrix(NA, ncol=0, nrow=5))

for(cutoff.scc in cutoffs)
{
  # Create dataframe:
  tmp <- as.data.frame(matrix(NA, nrow=3, ncol=2))
  colnames(tmp) <- c("TP", "TN")
  rownames(tmp) <- c("SCC+", "SCC-", " ")
  # Fill the table:
  tmp[1,1] <- length(dt[dt$SCC>=cutoff.scc & dt$inf%in%1]$SCC)
  tmp[1,2] <- length(dt[dt$SCC>=cutoff.scc & dt$inf%in%0]$SCC)
  tmp[2,1] <- length(dt[dt$SCC<cutoff.scc & dt$inf%in%1]$SCC)
  tmp[2,2] <- length(dt[dt$SCC<cutoff.scc & dt$inf%in%0]$SCC)
  #tmp
  tmp.sens <- tmp[1,1] / sum(tmp[1,1],tmp[2,1])
  tmp.spec <- tmp[2,2] / sum(tmp[1,2],tmp[2,2])
  tmp[3,] <- c("Se:", "Sp:")
  tmp[4,] <- round(c(tmp.sens,tmp.spec),2)
  tmp <- rbind(c(cutoff.scc, ""),tmp)
  res.tmp <- cbind(res.tmp,tmp)
}
colnames(res.tmp) <- NULL
rownames(res.tmp)[1] <- "Cutoff"
rownames(res.tmp)[5] <- "  "

res.tmp2 <- rbind(c(res.tmp[1,]), rep(c("TP", "TN"), length(cutoffs)), res.tmp[2:5,])
rownames(res.tmp2)[1] <- "Cutoff"
rownames(res.tmp2)[2] <- "   "

ROC for new / chronic infections

We then vary the cutoffs for SCC and DSCC and calculate the true positive rate and the false positive rate.

library(pROC)

scc.upper <- 15000

#### Herd 1, New infections: ####
dt <- alldata[Herd==1]

# First we look at SCC:
fp <- rep(NA, scc.upper)
tp <- rep(NA, scc.upper)
#
for(scc.cut in 1:scc.upper) # thousands. So from 1,000 to 1,000,000.
{
  fp[scc.cut] <- 1 / length(dt$SCC[dt$newinf%in%0]) * length(dt$SCC[dt$SCC>=scc.cut & dt$newinf%in%0])
  tp[scc.cut] <- 1 / length(dt$SCC[dt$newinf%in%1]) * length(dt$SCC[dt$SCC>=scc.cut & dt$newinf%in%1])
}

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(tp ~ fp, type="l", lwd=2, main="Herd 1, SCC, new infections")
abline(a=0, b=1, col="grey")

# SCC is not that good.

tp.h1.scc.ni <- tp
fp.h1.scc.ni <- fp

# Then we look at DSCC:
fp <- rep(NA, 100)
tp <- rep(NA, 100)
#
for(dscc.cut in 1:100) # thousands. So from 1,000 to 1,000,000.
{
  fp[dscc.cut] <- 1 / length(dt$SCC[dt$newinf%in%0]) * length(dt$DSCC[dt$DSCC>=dscc.cut & dt$newinf%in%0])
  tp[dscc.cut] <- 1 / length(dt$SCC[dt$newinf%in%1]) * length(dt$DSCC[dt$DSCC>=dscc.cut & dt$newinf%in%1])
}

par(mfrow=c(1,1))
plot(tp ~ fp, type="l", lwd=2, main="Herd 1, DSCC, new infections")
abline(a=0, b=1, col="grey")

# DSCC is not that good

tp.h1.dscc.ni <- tp
fp.h1.dscc.ni <- fp

Combined ROC

We can also look at a ROC curve for DSCC and SCC together. Here, both have to be above a threshold to indicate infection.

#### Herd 1, New infections: ####
dt <- alldata[Herd==1]

# Prøver lige med logSCC i stedet:
dt$logSCC <- log(dt$SCC)
res <- as.data.frame(matrix(ncol=150, nrow=100))
res.se <- as.data.frame(matrix(ncol=150, nrow=100))
res.sp <- as.data.frame(matrix(ncol=150, nrow=100))
Start <- Sys.time()
logscc.er <- seq(0.01,10,0.1)
for(dscc.cut in 1:100)
{
